WEBVTT

01:17.218 --> 01:22.926
Good morning everybody and everybody online as well as our campuses just wanna say glad you guys are here today.

01:22.946 --> 01:26.632
If you got your Bibles, go ahead and open up to Luke chapter 10, that's where we're gonna be.

01:26.692 --> 01:29.616
So Luke chapter 10, we're gonna start in verse 25.

01:30.497 --> 01:33.522
So if you guys got it with you, go ahead and open it up.

01:33.542 --> 01:36.727
And also if you don't mind, stand as we read God's word together.

01:36.747 --> 01:40.592
We're gonna be in Luke chapter 10 starting in verse 25.

01:40.672 --> 01:44.498
And it says, and behold, a lawyer stood up to put him to the test saying,

01:44.610 --> 01:47.353
Teacher, what shall I do to inherit eternal life?

01:47.473 --> 01:50.437
So he said to him, being Jesus, what is written in the law?

01:50.517 --> 01:51.899
How do you read it?

01:52.259 --> 01:59.188
And so he answered, you shall love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your strength, and with all your mind and your neighbor as yourself.

01:59.228 --> 02:03.212
And he said to him, you have answered correctly, do this and you will live.

02:03.693 --> 02:09.860
But designed to justify himself, he said to Jesus, who is my neighbor?

02:10.321 --> 02:14.546
So Jesus replied, a man was going down to Jerusalem from Jericho.

02:14.818 --> 02:19.927
from Jerusalem to Jericho and he fell among robbers who stripped him and beat him and departed leaving him half dead.

02:20.327 --> 02:25.175
Now by chance a priest was going down that road and when he saw him he passed by on the other side.

02:25.576 --> 02:36.274
So likewise a Levite when he came to the place and saw him passed by on the other side as well but a Samaritan as he journeyed came to where he was and when he saw him he had compassion so he went to him

02:36.450 --> 02:42.980
He bound up his wounds, pouring on oil and wine, and he set him on his own animal and brought him to an inn and took care of him.

02:43.000 --> 02:51.453
And then the next day, he took two denari and gave them to the innkeeper, saying, take care of him, and whatever more you spend, I will repay you when I come back.

02:51.513 --> 02:58.785
So in verse 36, which of these three, Jesus asked, do you think proved to be a neighbor to the man who fell among the robbers?

02:59.185 --> 03:02.130
So the man replied to the one who showed him mercy.

03:02.210 --> 03:05.794
And Jesus said to him, you go and do likewise.

03:05.834 --> 03:06.234
Let's pray.

03:06.294 --> 03:12.500
Thank you, Jesus, that we get an opportunity to be together today to read your word and to learn from it.

03:12.541 --> 03:19.788
So help us to do that, Father, that we would see it, we would understand it, but then we would go out and we would live it in the power of your Holy Spirit.

03:19.848 --> 03:20.288
And we pray.

03:20.709 --> 03:21.069
Amen.

03:21.089 --> 03:22.451
You guys, feel free to have a seat.

03:22.691 --> 03:23.652
Thank you so much.

03:24.192 --> 03:29.778
Man, I just got to tell you, we're starting off today and I told folks earlier that

03:30.050 --> 03:34.036
I'm excited just about today.

03:34.276 --> 03:38.543
Just this message, man, I've been hanging on to this for a couple of weeks now, actually more than that.

03:39.284 --> 03:47.996
I'm really more looking forward towards the end of the message, and I don't say amen because I know that you'll probably be agreeing with that, so just go with it.

03:48.697 --> 03:52.283
Our message series we continue today is High Impact.

03:52.323 --> 03:59.954
We talked about last week and we're going to continue to talk about today and the next week about how we as a church can have high impact, high amounts of influences,

04:00.162 --> 04:02.644
for the sake of the gospel in our community.

04:02.664 --> 04:05.708
And so we talked about being salt and light last week and what that looks like.

04:05.728 --> 04:12.434
And so today we're going to continue our series called High Impact and to start off on a share with you a story that comes from our Habersham campus.

04:13.335 --> 04:18.060
A few weeks ago, I was told about this guy that goes to our Habersham campus.

04:18.080 --> 04:19.802
His name is Cleat Honeycutt.

04:19.822 --> 04:28.370
And Cleat Honeycutt and some others from our church, they decided to get together and to go out and to serve someone in the community and do some work alongside someone

04:28.706 --> 04:36.737
And so they had this opportunity to work at a home and to help a lady be able to get into her bathroom because her wheelchair couldn't fit.

04:36.777 --> 04:43.526
And so they did some things around her bathroom, made it possible for her to be able to take a bath and no longer have to receive sponge bath.

04:43.586 --> 04:46.189
And so they did that work and they were thankful for that.

04:46.230 --> 04:51.677
But what was neat about the opportunity that they had is that not too long after that, Cleat was at Walmart.

04:52.238 --> 04:58.546
And while he was at Walmart, walking around the son of the family that they had, the house that they had worked at,

04:58.658 --> 05:05.053
walked up to him and he said, hey, aren't you the guy from Concord that came with some others and helped do what you did at our house?

05:05.073 --> 05:06.376
And he said, yeah, that's us.

05:06.477 --> 05:06.998
Absolutely.

05:07.539 --> 05:15.378
And so that young man went on to talk about how thankful he was and how thankful his family was that they had an opportunity to

05:15.522 --> 05:22.750
do that for his mom, and that's where I told you the story earlier about how for months that she had not been able to make it to her own bathroom to have a bath.

05:22.770 --> 05:32.061
But he explained that you guys have now given her something that she's been praying for for a while, and the family wrote cleat and others a note, and they said, we, the Monty family, ask God for help.

05:32.901 --> 05:40.310
And like the scripture says, asking you shall receive, God is good, and so are the Christians that come and repaired my home.

05:40.350 --> 05:44.114
We love you as Christians, Janice, Devon, and Jerry.

05:45.218 --> 05:46.200
So it's an amazing thing.

05:46.260 --> 05:50.888
I sent a cleat of text and I said, hey, you know, tell me a little bit about that.

05:50.949 --> 05:55.477
And he shared about it and just shared how it was a neat opportunity to be able to make that connection.

05:56.158 --> 06:04.754
And then not only make that connection to serve other people, but then look at the connection that they now have with that family that extends past the opportunity that they had to serve that weekend.

06:05.410 --> 06:20.931
And so when we choose to serve and we choose to do that when we're coming up in a couple of weeks with our serve weekend, that's our prayer is that out of that weekend, not only do we yes fulfill the call of serving and helping and meeting needs, but there would be further relationship for the glory of Jesus Christ following that day.

06:22.754 --> 06:34.450
And so that's the whole point of what we're doing this week in this month is talking about high impact, talking about stories like this and talking about what would it look like for more of this to happen in our context here in Northeast Georgia.

06:35.170 --> 06:38.794
And to do that, I want to pose to you a question, and this isn't really a question that I came up with.

06:38.814 --> 06:42.497
This is something that came out of the book, Transformational Church by Ed Stetser.

06:43.078 --> 06:51.767
But in the book, Ed Stetser asked this question, but we've made it for us this morning, is that if Concord ceased to exist, would the community even take notice?

06:51.787 --> 07:03.218
So as we're talking about high impact and high amounts of influence, and we're looking at what's going to happen in a couple of weeks, and the opportunity that we're going to have, when you think about our church and our community of faith here,

07:03.426 --> 07:07.552
Not just here in this location, but all of our other locations as well across Northeast Georgia.

07:08.313 --> 07:12.679
Thinking about this question, if we stopped existing today, would the community take notice?

07:13.460 --> 07:19.729
Not if this building disappeared, but if the people of Concord stopped doing what the people of Concord were doing.

07:21.191 --> 07:23.435
Would people take notice that there's less people serving?

07:23.455 --> 07:26.499
Would people take notice that there's less gospel presentation happening?

07:26.519 --> 07:31.346
Would people take notice that there's just salt and light in the area or would things remain the same?

07:32.450 --> 07:34.072
And it's a humbling question to think about.

07:35.033 --> 07:42.622
To think about what does it look like for us to collectively to really ask this question, which I think pertains to where we're going this morning, is do we neighbor well?

07:44.183 --> 07:52.232
As a body of believers gathered under the banner of Jesus Christ and entitled Concord Baptist Church, collectively, do we neighbor well?

07:54.775 --> 08:00.722
So this is a question for us together, and this is a question for us individually to explore as we jump in

08:00.802 --> 08:05.153
to what I think is probably a very familiar passage of scripture this morning, the Good Samaritan.

08:05.193 --> 08:14.195
When I think of the Good Samaritan, I think of this joke about the Sunday school class that this lady was leading of a four-year-old and she was going to tell the story of the Good Samaritan.

08:14.756 --> 08:17.202
And so she wanted to be as descriptive as possible.

08:17.570 --> 08:21.735
And so she wanted the four year olds to see in their minds everything that was happening.

08:21.755 --> 08:30.567
And so as she was talking and reading the good, the parable of the good Samaritan to her four year old, she was describing what the man would have went through and how he was left bloody on the side of the road.

08:30.627 --> 08:38.397
And so she asked the question, what do you think any of you would do if you were in this situation where you saw the man on the side of the road bleeding and dying?

08:38.938 --> 08:45.426
And it was kind of hushed over the crowd for a second, but then one four year old, honest little girl raised her hand and said, I think I would throw up.

08:46.946 --> 08:48.308
But isn't that all of us?

08:48.468 --> 08:49.991
We want to ask ourselves this question.

08:50.011 --> 08:51.733
When we're in this situation, what would we do?

08:52.675 --> 08:53.576
And what do we do?

08:54.718 --> 08:57.523
Because a lot of times, yes, we would look at that situation and go, you know what?

08:57.563 --> 08:59.045
I don't want to get in that.

08:59.065 --> 09:00.087
That makes me a little queasy.

09:00.107 --> 09:01.689
That makes me a little uneasy.

09:01.709 --> 09:08.259
I know what it's going to take for me to jump into that situation of service and what could happen because of that in my life.

09:09.281 --> 09:15.090
But I think what we're going to see this morning from Luke in the story of the parable of the Good Samaritan that Jesus told to teach a point

09:15.426 --> 09:29.822
I think we're going to be inspired to look past what could happen to us and how our schedules might get wrecked and how our agendas might get messed up to really still pursue the answer to this question is, do we neighbor well?

09:30.343 --> 09:34.107
And that our community around us would answer this for us and they would say yes.

09:35.168 --> 09:40.434
And so Luke chapter 10 verse 25 is where we start and behold, a lawyer stood up to put him

09:40.642 --> 09:41.503
to the test.

09:41.523 --> 09:44.527
Now this wasn't a lawyer kind of like we think about in our today's terms.

09:44.588 --> 09:49.334
It's more of a lawyer of someone who was maybe in your text that actually says an expert of the law.

09:49.354 --> 09:58.167
It was someone who studied the Old Testament and they knew the Old Testament inside and out and they could tell you what the law said and what you were supposed to do and when you were supposed to do it and everything that you were supposed to carry out.

09:58.587 --> 10:03.314
And so this was someone that was very learned and also very elite when it came to Jewish social status.

10:03.874 --> 10:09.964
And so this was the guy that came to Jesus and he wanted to ask him a question so that he could test Jesus.

10:09.984 --> 10:17.856
And the word test there and what we understand from the text is that he wasn't asking because he was trying to get something out of it so that he could go away and do it.

10:18.216 --> 10:21.962
He was trying to ask it from an antagonistic standpoint to trick Jesus.

10:22.663 --> 10:32.018
To put Jesus in a situation where maybe all of the people that were kind of starting to pay attention to Jesus would stop paying attention to Jesus and then would begin start paying attention to this guy again.

10:32.994 --> 10:35.117
And so it was an antagonistic question, a test.

10:35.838 --> 10:41.505
So he says, teacher, what must I, what can I do to inherit eternal life?

10:42.947 --> 10:46.672
What do I do in order that eternal life will be handed to me as what the gentleman said?

10:47.573 --> 10:50.757
And so Jesus replied, he said to him, what is written in the law?

10:51.358 --> 10:52.079
And how do you read it?

10:53.641 --> 10:57.266
So what Jesus was doing was affirming that him and him and the sky were on level ground.

10:58.050 --> 11:01.895
Because what was written in the law, what was written in the Old Testament is what was final.

11:01.935 --> 11:04.418
Just like what is written in the complete word of God is final.

11:04.438 --> 11:05.779
What God has said is final.

11:05.799 --> 11:06.280
It is done.

11:06.320 --> 11:06.841
It is finished.

11:06.861 --> 11:08.823
He has spoken, therefore we must do.

11:08.863 --> 11:10.505
So Jesus said, what is written?

11:10.545 --> 11:13.128
Because whatever is written, then that's what we are to do.

11:13.168 --> 11:14.910
And so he asked the man, what is written?

11:14.950 --> 11:15.951
How do you read it?

11:16.032 --> 11:16.873
How do you interpret it?

11:18.294 --> 11:21.658
And so the man replies, he says, well, you should love the Lord your God.

11:21.738 --> 11:23.020
So he gets that from Deuteronomy.

11:23.501 --> 11:24.722
It's known as the Shema.

11:25.250 --> 11:29.274
You love the Lord your God with all your heart, with all your soul, with all your strength, and with all your mind.

11:29.795 --> 11:32.878
And then you will love your neighbor as yourself.

11:33.438 --> 11:47.072
So those two things joined together, joined together indicates that not only Jesus, but others had an understanding that the whole law was summed up in following these two things, loving God with all your heart and loving your neighbor as yourself.

11:47.653 --> 11:53.138
And if it wasn't this guy's idea that he had gotten it from, then maybe he had heard Jesus already talk about, but regardless,

11:53.410 --> 12:02.585
They were both in agreeance because what Jesus said next, you have said or you have answered correctly, do this and you will live.

12:03.526 --> 12:10.257
So according to the self righteous pursuit of this man, he had gotten what he needed to get out of this situation so far.

12:11.739 --> 12:13.963
Because what he was seeking was self justification.

12:14.444 --> 12:15.986
I want to make sure I'm good enough.

12:16.898 --> 12:23.408
And so when he asked, when he asked Jesus the question and then Jesus responds, you're correct in saying that you love God and you love your neighbor as yourself.

12:23.468 --> 12:24.590
And you, you said it.

12:24.630 --> 12:26.092
So you're good to go way to go.

12:26.212 --> 12:29.176
You know, that's, if you're looking for a pat on the back, that's what the guy was getting.

12:30.338 --> 12:41.876
And if you ever in life, and I do this probably more than anybody, you get in the situation in the conversation and it gets to the point where you probably should just walk away and stop talking.

12:42.537 --> 12:46.162
You know, like I've learned this in marriage that at some point in the conversation, it's best just to hush.

12:47.074 --> 12:50.759
And this is that moment in this situation, in this text.

12:51.500 --> 13:00.832
You know, we don't really see it, but this is where at any, at this moment, this guy should have taken off the size 10 sandal that he was wearing and put it in his mouth and walked away.

13:01.553 --> 13:02.495
But he had to speak up.

13:04.657 --> 13:09.424
And so I would imagine like maybe the, maybe Jesus was kind of like, okay, conversation's over.

13:09.464 --> 13:12.928
I'm gonna give this guy, you know, we're kind of maybe, and maybe Jesus was turning.

13:13.229 --> 13:15.592
Maybe like he was finishing, maybe gonna answer someone else's question.

13:15.612 --> 13:17.074
I don't know, we can't, you know,

13:17.218 --> 13:18.460
come up with reality there.

13:18.640 --> 13:25.489
We're only left to what the text says, but we do know that the man was getting what he needed, but he opened his mouth.

13:26.470 --> 13:33.079
And when he opened his mouth, desiring to justify himself, who is my neighbor?

13:34.721 --> 13:40.168
And at that moment, maybe there was a smile that came across our Savior's face and he's like, all right, here we go.

13:41.550 --> 13:44.434
Because really, this guy wasn't really asking this question.

13:45.442 --> 13:54.436
We read it and we see who is my neighbor, but there's actually two different questions that are being asked, one by the lawyer and then the other by Jesus that he's gonna ask later.

13:55.277 --> 14:00.625
And so for the lawyer, what he was asking is what must a person do to qualify that I should treat them as a neighbor?

14:00.665 --> 14:02.428
That's what he was asking.

14:02.448 --> 14:09.238
He was really getting at like, well, how do you know who's living in such a way that I should treat them as a neighbor and love them?

14:09.659 --> 14:11.181
Like, let's get at that.

14:12.182 --> 14:14.546
And before we like, test, test, this guy,

14:14.946 --> 14:16.849
How many times do we act this way, right?

14:18.231 --> 14:19.392
What do they have to do?

14:19.793 --> 14:23.999
What decisions should they have made in the past that would put them in the place that they now deserve my love?

14:24.760 --> 14:27.664
What do they have to look like or act like or wear or dress?

14:27.804 --> 14:34.514
Or what racial class should they come from in order for me to extend love for them the way that Jesus wants me to extend love from them?

14:35.170 --> 14:37.093
We have our list of qualifications as well.

14:37.133 --> 14:44.884
So let us be careful and not passing blame off to this guy and saying, uh, shame on you for asking what qualified someone to receive your love.

14:46.386 --> 14:48.048
But that's what the lawyer was indeed asking.

14:48.128 --> 14:49.811
What must someone do?

14:50.552 --> 14:52.174
But this is what Jesus said.

14:52.254 --> 14:55.759
Jesus was asking the other question and you're going to see it later.

14:55.799 --> 14:57.001
What must I do?

14:57.962 --> 14:59.605
This is other centered.

14:59.745 --> 15:00.466
In other words,

15:00.610 --> 15:02.692
What do they have to do to receive my love?

15:03.092 --> 15:07.477
Jesus is going to get the man to think about what must I do to be a loving neighbor.

15:08.478 --> 15:09.439
What must we do?

15:09.539 --> 15:13.943
What must you do to be a loving neighbor?

15:13.963 --> 15:20.550
And so right here in the middle of the crowd, this man's heart is put on the dissection table.

15:21.491 --> 15:28.658
He should have just walked away, kept his mouth closed, but like right now Jesus is about to expose his heart and our heart.

15:29.506 --> 15:31.228
And he does it through a story.

15:32.190 --> 15:35.314
And so he says, a man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho.

15:35.334 --> 15:39.239
Because anytime you left Jerusalem, he always went down somewhere because it was on a mountain.

15:39.259 --> 15:45.648
So from Jerusalem to Jericho and he fell among the robbers who stripped him and they beat him and departed, leaving him half dead.

15:46.168 --> 15:58.285
Now by chance, a priest, someone who was a descendant of Aaron, someone who maintained the temple, someone who did sacrifices, someone who had extensive religious duty and knew all the answers.

15:58.385 --> 15:59.186
This is the guy.

15:59.714 --> 16:02.276
Now, a priest, everybody would have been like, oh, here we go.

16:02.377 --> 16:03.277
It's about to get good.

16:03.818 --> 16:08.763
Now, a priest was going down the road, and when he saw me pass by the other side, and I would see people probably scratching their heads, huh?

16:08.803 --> 16:10.084
This guy was supposed to stop.

16:10.564 --> 16:10.965
You're right.

16:11.405 --> 16:13.127
So then a Levite shows up.

16:13.147 --> 16:18.172
And likewise, he came to the same place, and he saw him, and he passed by on the other side as well.

16:18.192 --> 16:21.755
So you have two people considered very religious elite people in the day.

16:21.795 --> 16:22.656
They knew all the answers.

16:22.676 --> 16:23.376
They knew what to say.

16:23.417 --> 16:24.137
They knew what to do.

16:24.397 --> 16:26.239
They knew the Old Testament backwards and forwards.

16:27.080 --> 16:29.202
The two people that you have expected to stop

16:29.858 --> 16:30.519
didn't stop.

16:31.179 --> 16:40.988
This was brilliant on Jesus' part because Jesus loved telling stories and parables, but one of the things that's interesting is that this was kind of a storytelling trick that people would do all the time.

16:41.008 --> 16:47.254
When they wanted to teach a lesson, they would use the religious elite like priests and Levite to teach a lesson about how to live.

16:47.895 --> 16:59.666
And so at the moment, the people would have been tuned in to expect something next because if he's already mentioned a priest, and he's already mentioned a Levite, but those two people didn't do the thing that they were supposed to do, well then who is left?

17:00.386 --> 17:04.612
And so they're, they're probably thinking like at some other religious elite person in the Jewish society.

17:04.953 --> 17:08.498
And then Jesus throws this out there and he says, but a Samaritan.

17:09.760 --> 17:15.449
Now if you've ever read the parable of the good Samaritan, you know that this is the most unlikely of characters to have stopped.

17:17.052 --> 17:23.281
And it wasn't something like a, it wasn't something like a Georgia tech, Georgia rivalry or an Alabama, Auburn rivalry that these people had.

17:23.301 --> 17:26.546
This was racial tension that was steeped in 800 years.

17:28.098 --> 17:29.820
And so these people did not like each other.

17:29.840 --> 17:31.462
They disagreed on so many things.

17:31.482 --> 17:33.525
They disagreed on where to worship God.

17:33.565 --> 17:35.227
They disagreed on how to worship God.

17:35.247 --> 17:37.109
They disagreed on who God's people were.

17:37.129 --> 17:43.337
It was the tension could be cut with a knife in this moment.

17:44.118 --> 17:48.403
There might have been people that spit on the ground at this moment in the mention of this person's name.

17:49.144 --> 17:53.870
But it's just a fictitious person, but Jesus says, but a Samaritan, as he journeyed, he came to the place where he was.

17:54.350 --> 17:56.093
And when he saw him, he had compassion on him.

17:56.133 --> 17:57.234
So he went up to him.

17:58.370 --> 18:01.454
And he went up to him and he bound his wounds and pouring on oil and wine.

18:01.474 --> 18:05.819
And then he sat him on his own animal and brought him to an end and took care of him.

18:05.839 --> 18:15.331
And then the next day, he took out his own money to Daenera and gave them to the innkeeper saying, take care of him and whatever more you spend, I will repay you when I come back.

18:15.371 --> 18:19.035
And then Jesus asked the question, which of these people, which of these three?

18:20.096 --> 18:24.442
Do you think proved to be a neighbor to the man who fell among the robbers?

18:25.663 --> 18:26.764
And we all know the answer.

18:26.784 --> 18:28.146
The question was obvious here.

18:29.410 --> 18:37.638
But what Jesus was bringing it back to that question of not so much, what does someone have to do to qualify to get the love that I'm going to give them?

18:38.499 --> 18:40.861
But instead, what do I do to be a good neighbor?

18:41.742 --> 18:44.905
Or who, who should I consider myself to be a neighbor to?

18:44.965 --> 18:47.247
Who should I consider to be my neighbor?

18:48.188 --> 18:50.390
That was the heart of what Jesus was trying to get at.

18:50.771 --> 18:52.272
Who should I consider to be my neighbor?

18:52.352 --> 18:55.475
Jesus was answering it in the form of a parable by saying, everyone.

18:56.616 --> 18:58.418
Everyone is considered a neighbor.

18:59.874 --> 19:09.044
There is no one by racial class, socioeconomic status, or by simply looking at them, do you get to decide whether or not you do not get to show compassion to them?

19:09.104 --> 19:13.208
Because everyone is your neighbor.

19:13.228 --> 19:16.912
And so in verse 37, when he asked the man, he said, who do you think it was?

19:16.992 --> 19:23.218
Notice that the man couldn't even say the words of Maryton, that he actually says, the one who showed him mercy.

19:24.119 --> 19:26.642
And Jesus said to him, go and do likewise.

19:28.898 --> 19:30.440
Go and do likewise.

19:30.720 --> 19:32.422
Who should you be a neighbor to?

19:32.482 --> 19:33.463
Everyone.

19:33.984 --> 19:35.365
That's the answer there.

19:35.866 --> 19:38.529
Who was a neighbor to the person that was on the side of the road?

19:39.329 --> 19:40.471
The Samaritan man was.

19:40.991 --> 19:42.092
Now go and do likewise.

19:42.173 --> 19:44.855
Go and show compassion the same way that this person have.

19:44.875 --> 19:47.438
And so there's three things that we can take away from this.

19:47.498 --> 19:51.963
Three choices of servanthood that we need to learn from this passage and from the life of Jesus.

19:52.003 --> 19:54.546
And that is number one that we need to choose to see the need.

19:55.618 --> 20:06.916
That just like Jesus chose to see the need of the people around him, just like he lived in a way where his eyes were open and attentive to what the need was, both physical, emotional and spiritual, we need to choose to see the need as well.

20:07.357 --> 20:08.479
That we need to open our eyes.

20:08.519 --> 20:09.140
We need to pray.

20:09.160 --> 20:10.142
We need to be on the lookout.

20:10.162 --> 20:17.954
We need to be expecting that God would place before us an opportunity where we get to extend the love of Christ to other people, both through word and through works.

20:18.976 --> 20:22.642
So we need to choose to see the need, but then secondly, we got to choose to roll up our sleeves.

20:23.362 --> 20:26.386
And this is the hard part because once you roll up your sleeves, you know what's going to happen.

20:26.406 --> 20:27.347
Your hands are going to get dirty.

20:28.828 --> 20:33.234
Just like the man who stopped on the side of the road, the Samaritan that stopped to help the man, he had to roll his sleeves up.

20:33.254 --> 20:34.035
He had to do something.

20:34.075 --> 20:35.176
He had to get bloody.

20:35.196 --> 20:36.057
He had to get dirty.

20:36.117 --> 20:47.250
And I would say more than likely number two is probably the reason that I really never have much success in jumping into serving opportunities is because I know it's going to take rolling up my sleeves.

20:48.322 --> 20:49.143
It's going to get messy.

20:49.163 --> 20:58.714
And for some of you who have served before, for some of you that have poured out your own resources, your own heart, your own love, your own life to serve other people, at some point you have learned that ministry is messy.

21:00.115 --> 21:08.665
You have learned that loving others and serving them is a messy thing, but don't miss the fact that Jesus is trying to teach us that that still should not keep us from showing compassion.

21:09.506 --> 21:13.490
So we've got to roll up our sleeves, but then number three, we've got to choose to neighbor well.

21:15.202 --> 21:16.964
These are choices that we have to make.

21:17.004 --> 21:18.947
These are things that Jesus is calling us to do.

21:19.348 --> 21:21.350
Serving others is not always easy.

21:23.093 --> 21:25.115
Matter of fact, it's like really never easy.

21:27.298 --> 21:32.705
It might be easy in the moment once you get into it because you realize like God had that for you and he is empowering you to do that.

21:33.026 --> 21:36.991
But before you step into it, there is something about us in our nature that says no.

21:38.453 --> 21:40.256
And it's because we're sinful, selfish creatures.

21:41.898 --> 21:45.042
And we want everything for ourselves and everything to be about us.

21:46.882 --> 22:01.346
You know, when we think about choosing to neighbor well, when it talks about Jesus and John chapter one, that he was the word and he was in the beginning and he was always there and Jesus wasn't created, but he was there in the beginning and everything that was created was created through him and for him.

22:01.747 --> 22:08.338
And then it says later on down in John one, it says that he then came into the world and made his dwelling among us.

22:09.314 --> 22:10.656
That word used tabernacle.

22:10.696 --> 22:12.057
He moved into the neighborhood.

22:12.097 --> 22:17.603
If Jesus was in your neighborhood, your physical neighborhood, or in our community, what kind of neighbor would Jesus be?

22:18.444 --> 22:19.285
What would Jesus do?

22:19.305 --> 22:20.907
We don't have to guess.

22:20.947 --> 22:25.632
We don't have to come up with these subjective reasons of like, well, maybe he would do this, maybe he would do that.

22:25.893 --> 22:26.994
We just got to read the word.

22:28.095 --> 22:29.697
It's not what did, what would Jesus do?

22:29.757 --> 22:30.578
What did Jesus do?

22:31.779 --> 22:33.661
And what Jesus did was taught us to neighbor well.

22:33.701 --> 22:37.906
So we need to be willing to ask the question is, what should I do to neighbor well?

22:38.690 --> 22:52.930
And then whatever response comes into your mind, whatever Holy Spirit prompts you to move to in order to neighbor well in our community, whatever it is he prompts you to do in your neighborhood, in your home, in your business, in your school, and wherever it is you are to serve others and neighbor well.

22:53.291 --> 22:56.776
Whatever you get prompted to do, my prayer is that you would step towards that.

22:58.999 --> 23:03.826
And that's the point of serve weekend coming up and what we're hoping to see happen is that as we answer this question,

23:04.386 --> 23:10.593
What if Concord ceased to exist with the community notice, we would love for the community to be able to say a resounding yes?

23:12.956 --> 23:18.602
That they would look at Concord and if we stop doing what we stop doing, that people in the community would take notice.

23:19.683 --> 23:25.470
And that we would choose to see those needs and roll up our sleeves and that we would choose to neighbor well anyone that comes into contact with us.

23:26.971 --> 23:29.394
But there's a deep truth that we need to know about this story.

23:30.306 --> 23:32.028
Remember how I told you, I was excited about the end.

23:32.048 --> 23:32.709
Well, here it comes.

23:32.729 --> 23:34.291
So you're probably saying, amen, here it comes.

23:35.652 --> 23:40.798
But really the reality of this story is that we're not the good Samaritan.

23:42.640 --> 23:54.273
The person that pours out his life, his resources, his own power to help someone that by cultural standards is considered an enemy of the man that stopped to help him is not a picture of us.

23:54.994 --> 23:58.418
It's actually a picture of Jesus that Jesus is the good Samaritan in this story.

23:59.234 --> 24:04.162
Let me ask you a question, what if instead we were primarily like the guy that is on the side of the road?

24:06.125 --> 24:17.504
The commission, the commission to love and neighbor well, and then our response to that or our lack of response to that might have something to do with how we see ourselves in this story.

24:18.986 --> 24:22.572
Let me ask you this, what do you think the expert in the law, the lawyer?

24:23.734 --> 24:26.418
What do you think he would have discovered

24:27.138 --> 24:29.603
after he heard the words go and do this.

24:30.865 --> 24:36.095
Like if he would legitimately, because more than likely we know, like he was trying to trick Jesus, it wasn't about his heart.

24:36.115 --> 24:40.102
It was about trying to put himself in a place where people would see him as better than Jesus.

24:40.162 --> 24:45.953
And so we know he wasn't trying to make a spiritual step and take the next step in his faith, but he was trying to trick Jesus.

24:46.955 --> 24:48.658
But if, if, if,

24:49.154 --> 24:52.079
He would have walked out of that situation and what it says, you know what?

24:52.480 --> 24:54.123
I'm going to go and do what Jesus said.

24:54.143 --> 24:55.265
Do you know what he would have realized?

24:55.285 --> 25:04.622
I think it's the same thing that we realize when we walk out of these doors every day, when we vacate the premises, when we leave our community groups, when we leave hanging out with other Christians and they encourage us and then we say, you know what?

25:04.642 --> 25:05.283
Let's go and do it.

25:05.303 --> 25:13.458
You know what we realize is that for us really go and do is really a go and try because we get out there and we try and we try and we try again and we fail.

25:14.754 --> 25:19.821
And the reason that we fail is because we see ourselves in this story as the good Samaritan, but in reality, it's Jesus.

25:21.704 --> 25:27.391
That what this story has really tried to teach us is that in our depravity, we don't have the ability to love well.

25:27.411 --> 25:33.560
We don't have the ability to neighbor well, that a relationship with God can never be based on human accomplishments or human works.

25:34.000 --> 25:34.922
No one can do this.

25:35.102 --> 25:39.007
No one can fulfill the law of love, of loving God and loving your neighbor well.

25:39.087 --> 25:41.010
We can't do it on our own.

25:42.530 --> 25:54.152
And the truth of it is that we are all in or were, currently are, whatever it is that we all were in a ditch of our own sin left by the side of the road to die on our own without any help whatsoever.

25:54.193 --> 26:03.250
And there was nothing we could do to crawl out of the ditch until a man stopped by, poured out his blood, poured out his life and poured out his resources and is offering you the hand of grace and mercy.

26:05.538 --> 26:07.980
And so this story is not about what we can do.

26:08.061 --> 26:12.125
It's more about what Jesus has already done and is allowing us to be a part of this.

26:12.205 --> 26:13.586
And yes, we have to see this.

26:14.647 --> 26:19.692
And we have to neighbor well, this is an excuse for us to walk out of here and go, all right, what do I have to do anything?

26:22.455 --> 26:28.921
The purpose of this story is for us to see the depravity of our own condition that we would look and we would go, man, that is hard.

26:30.463 --> 26:31.083
Like I get it.

26:32.305 --> 26:33.746
And I think Jesus got it too.

26:34.338 --> 26:37.083
More than likely, that guy walked away depressed from the situation.

26:37.203 --> 26:42.754
One, because his pride was hurt, but two, he might have come to grips with the reality that he is a sinful and depraved human being.

26:44.336 --> 26:51.530
And when I look at my life and sometimes the opportunities that I don't take to help and to serve other people, it comes because of the view I have of myself.

26:54.014 --> 26:58.162
But instead of looking at myself, I need to look to the identity of Christ.

26:59.874 --> 27:06.785
See what Jesus was trying to teach this man is not a bunch of new rules that he needs to go and to live by, but rather he was giving him a new reality to live in.

27:08.548 --> 27:09.690
Don't go and do more.

27:09.750 --> 27:14.899
Don't go and try and do more of what you've been trying to do on your own.

27:15.239 --> 27:17.904
Stop living with a list of rules of do's and don'ts.

27:17.924 --> 27:20.588
Start living in the reality that it's already done for you.

27:20.648 --> 27:26.738
And then from that as an expression of love and gratitude because of what Jesus has done on the cross, that's how you love people.

27:28.674 --> 27:30.456
And this changes the way that we serve.

27:30.476 --> 27:33.700
This changes the way that we minister to people.

27:34.320 --> 27:36.202
We stop looking at ourselves as the hero.

27:36.222 --> 27:44.752
We start, we stop looking at ourselves when we don't do things and putting ourselves down and getting into these states where we're like, well, I can't do anything or it's too many problems in the world.

27:44.772 --> 27:45.593
There's too much hurt.

27:45.833 --> 27:51.619
We stop looking at it from that standpoint and we start looking at what Jesus did on the cross and we start going, it's possible.

27:53.621 --> 27:57.906
But not only, it's possible not because of anything we have, but because of what he did.

27:58.850 --> 28:01.114
It's not a bunch of new rules that Jesus came to give us.

28:01.194 --> 28:05.542
It's a new reality that He came to help us live in and to help us live out of.

28:05.643 --> 28:08.969
In 1 John 4 19, it says, we love because He first loved us.

28:10.211 --> 28:11.413
This is the new reality.

28:14.479 --> 28:16.082
There's no rule in this.

28:17.474 --> 28:27.926
that living and serving other people and participating in serve weekend or doing it across here or doing it across our communities isn't because of an expression of a bunch of new rules that we were handed on a Sunday morning.

28:27.946 --> 28:30.929
It's an expression of the new reality that Jesus is allowing you to live in.

28:30.949 --> 28:45.746
I mean, if you walk away from anything today, like just these two words is all you need because he, because he lives, we can face tomorrow because he lives because he went to the cross.

28:46.562 --> 28:53.832
So maybe today, maybe some of you have been thinking about like being a part of serve weekend, or you know, maybe you're thinking about getting involved.

28:53.852 --> 29:05.828
We would love that you would get involved, but not because we're asking or not because you feel guilted into it, but that you would go back to this because he, because he has done something amazing in your life.

29:07.471 --> 29:09.874
And maybe some, and maybe just maybe,

29:10.530 --> 29:17.158
As we start seeing what Jesus has done for us, it will then compel us to actually go out and to serve in the same manner with which He served us.

29:20.682 --> 29:26.849
So because He, because He we can, we can live in a new reality serving and loving others around us.

29:27.169 --> 29:28.891
Let's pray.

29:28.911 --> 29:29.552
Thank you, Jesus.

29:30.973 --> 29:38.642
Your gospel is so good that you would love a sinner, a sinner like me,

29:39.714 --> 30:04.542
that you would down across, just like all of us in the room, we were once in the ditch of our own sin, left to, left to our own demise, but you and your grace and your mercy decided to come down and to live with us and to take on our sin and our shame.

30:05.943 --> 30:06.864
Heads bowed, eyes closed.

30:06.884 --> 30:08.306
That's what Jesus did for you.

30:10.210 --> 30:20.425
Each one of us in the room, we're left to our own demise and our own sin separated from God for all of eternity, hanging onto our sin, walking towards our death.

30:22.047 --> 30:23.890
But Jesus took your sin on the cross.

30:25.172 --> 30:31.701
He died your death and then it was raised from the dead to prove that he had the power over sin and death in your life.

30:33.344 --> 30:37.810
And this morning, maybe what you need to do is you need to wake up and realize maybe the Holy Spirit is

30:38.658 --> 30:42.704
moving in your heart for the first time and he is bringing you out of death into life.

30:43.625 --> 30:49.093
He is pulling you out of the ditch and he is setting you back, he is setting you on the path to follow him.

30:50.636 --> 30:56.064
Bible says if you would just repent from your sin and turn and follow him, you have new life.

30:56.104 --> 30:57.846
Confess it with your mouth, believe in your heart.

30:59.248 --> 31:05.938
So if you're here this morning or your own line or across one of our campuses and you want to make that decision, we would love to celebrate that with you.

31:07.074 --> 31:08.536
We're gonna have a time of invitation.

31:09.096 --> 31:10.618
We'd love to talk about what that looks like.

31:10.638 --> 31:11.679
Don't be afraid to come down.

31:11.719 --> 31:14.382
Don't be afraid to talk about how you know you need to come out of the ditch.

31:16.945 --> 31:25.013
But also if you're here today and you've been thinking about joining our church, partnering with us in ministry, we'd love to talk to you about that as well to make that decision.

31:28.557 --> 31:33.362
So all across the room, if you all will, we're gonna stand and close in a word of prayer and then another song.

31:34.018 --> 31:38.164
So Jesus, we pray that you be blessed and honored in all that we say, in all that we do.

31:38.828 --> 31:39.472
In your name we pray.

31:40.640 --> 31:41.042
Amen.

